Qualitative Analysis of Analytical Decisions

Alex Kale

9/5/2018

Load Codes

Load in codes from qualitative analysis of analytical decisions.

codes <- read.csv(file="codes-anonymous.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")

This spreadsheet was constructed through an iterative qualitative coding procedure described in the paper.

Frequencies of Strategies

Looking at the frequency of each kind of strategy used by our participants to manage uncertainty in decisions about analysis paths, we can see that reducing uncertainty is by far the most prevalent strategy, followed by acknowledgement and suppression.

# counts of strategies
d.strat <- data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes$Decision)*100
)

This is approximately what we would hope to see insofar as decisions to reduce uncertainty are most prevalent and decisions to suppress uncertainty are least prevalent.

Frequencies of Strategies by Context of Mention

Let’s take a look at all decisions vs firsthand accounts vs secondhand accounts vs hypothetical scenarios to see if there is a difference in the distribution of strategies. We’ll look at percentages as well as raw frequencies of decisions.

# add column to data table of strategies for type of mention
d.strat.mention <- cbind(d.strat,"Mention"=c("All","All","All"))

# get counts of strategies for:
# firsthand accounts
codes.firsthand <- codes %>% filter(Mention=="Firsthand")
d.strat.mention <- rbind(d.strat.mention, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.firsthand$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.firsthand$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.firsthand$Strategy=='Suppress')),
    "Percent"=c(sum(codes.firsthand$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.firsthand$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.firsthand$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.firsthand$Decision)*100,
  "Mention"=c("Firsthand","Firsthand","Firsthand")
))
# secondhand accounts
codes.secondhand <- codes %>% filter(Mention=="Secondhand")
d.strat.mention <- rbind(d.strat.mention, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.secondhand$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.secondhand$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.secondhand$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.secondhand$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.secondhand$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.secondhand$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.secondhand$Decision)*100,
  "Mention"=c("Secondhand","Secondhand","Secondhand")
))
# hypothetical accounts
codes.hypothetical <- codes %>% filter(Mention=="Hypothetical")
d.strat.mention <- rbind(d.strat.mention, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.hypothetical$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.hypothetical$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.hypothetical$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.hypothetical$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.hypothetical$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.hypothetical$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.hypothetical$Decision)*100,
  "Mention"=c("Hypothetical","Hypothetical","Hypothetical")
))

We can see the distibution of decisions across our three kinds of strategies is relatively similar regardless of the kind of mention. Note that the set of all decisions regardless of mention resembles the subsets of firsthand accounts and hypothetical scenarios only. With only 10 observations, it is hard to say much about secondhand accounts based on our codes. Looking at the pie charts showing proportions of each strategy for each kind of mention, we can see that our participants used a strategy of acknowledging uncertainty relatively more, and used a strategy of reducing uncertainty relatively less, in hypothetical scenarios than in accounts of firsthand experiences. Perhaps the scenarios which were posed as hypotheticals by participants during our interviews were more often intractable situations where there was not a clear path to reduce uncertainty. (I will look for some examples if we want to talk about this in the paper.)

Frequencies of Strategies by Direct vs Indirect Impact

Let’s look at the frequencies of strategies for decisions with direct vs indirect impact. We’ll look at percentages as well as raw frequencies of decisions.

# add column to data table of strategies for type of mention
d.strat.impact <- cbind(d.strat,"Impact"=c("Both","Both","Both"))

# get counts of strategies for decisions with:
# direct impact
codes.direct <- codes %>% filter(Impact=="Direct")
d.strat.impact <- rbind(d.strat.impact, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.direct$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.direct$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.direct$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.direct$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.direct$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.direct$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.direct$Decision)*100,
  "Impact"=c("Direct","Direct","Direct")
))
# indirect impact
codes.indirect <- codes %>% filter(Impact=="Indirect")
d.strat.impact <- rbind(d.strat.impact, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.indirect$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.indirect$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.indirect$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.indirect$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.indirect$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.indirect$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.indirect$Decision)*100,
  "Impact"=c("Indirect","Indirect","Indirect")
))

We can see that decisions with indirect impact were more often a instances of an acknowledgement strategy than a reduction strategy. This may reflect the fact that decisions with direct impact are decisions about:

  • what to look for in the literature,
  • what to include in the review,
  • what to code in an evidence table,
  • how to incorporate evidence into the final written report.

These are predominantly rule-based decisions (i.e., reduction). Whereas decisions with indirect impact are decisions which don’t change the content of the written report, such as decisions about:

  • review team management,
  • process documentation,
  • checking data quality, risk of bias in studies, and publication bias in the review (unless participants explicitly state that these checks are included in the report or are used to inform inclusion/exclusion),
  • presentation details like visualization layouts and nuaces of framing,
  • what to include in a brief presentation.

Many of these decisions serve the purpose of steering the implementation of scientific process and organizing collaboration among researchers (i.e., acknowledgement). That being said there is still a substantial amount of reduction in decisions with indirect impact.

Frequencies of Strategies per Stage of Analysis

Next, we look at frequencies and percentages of each strategy at each stage in the analysis process.

# add column to data table of strategies for type of mention
d.strat.stage <- cbind(d.strat,"Stage"=c("Overall","Overall","Overall"))

# get counts of strategies at the stage of:
# questions
codes.questions <- codes %>% filter(Stage.of.Analysis=="Defining questions and objectives")
d.strat.stage <- rbind(d.strat.stage, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.questions$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.questions$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.questions$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.questions$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.questions$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.questions$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.questions$Decision)*100,
  "Stage"=c("Define Questions","Define Questions","Define Questions")
))
# literature review
codes.review <- codes %>% filter(Stage.of.Analysis=="Literature review")
d.strat.stage <- rbind(d.strat.stage, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.review$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.review$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.review$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.review$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.review$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.review$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.review$Decision)*100,
  "Stage"=c("Lit Review","Lit Review","Lit Review")
))
# data collection
codes.collect <- codes %>% filter(Stage.of.Analysis=="Data collection")
d.strat.stage <- rbind(d.strat.stage, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.collect$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.collect$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.collect$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.collect$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.collect$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.collect$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.collect$Decision)*100,
  "Stage"=c("Data Collection","Data Collection","Data Collection")
))
# meta-analysis
codes.meta <- codes %>% filter(Stage.of.Analysis=="Meta-analysis")
d.strat.stage <- rbind(d.strat.stage, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.meta$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.meta$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.meta$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.meta$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.meta$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.meta$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.meta$Decision)*100,
  "Stage"=c("Meta-Analysis","Meta-Analysis","Meta-Analysis")
))
# quantitative analysis
codes.quant <- codes %>% filter(Stage.of.Analysis=="Quantitative Analysis")
d.strat.stage <- rbind(d.strat.stage, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.quant$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.quant$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.quant$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.quant$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.quant$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.quant$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.quant$Decision)*100,
  "Stage"=c("Quant Analysis","Quant Analysis","Quant Analysis")
))
# qualitative analysis
codes.qual <- codes %>% filter(Stage.of.Analysis=="Qualitative analysis")
d.strat.stage <- rbind(d.strat.stage, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.qual$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.qual$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.qual$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.qual$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.qual$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.qual$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.qual$Decision)*100,
  "Stage"=c("Qual Analysis","Qual Analysis","Qual Analysis")
))
# communication
codes.comm <- codes %>% filter(Stage.of.Analysis=="Communication")
d.strat.stage <- rbind(d.strat.stage, data.frame(
  "Strategy"=c('Acknowledge','Reduce','Suppress'),
  "Frequency"=c(sum(codes.comm$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.comm$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.comm$Strategy=='Suppress')),
  "Percent"=c(sum(codes.comm$Strategy=='Acknowledge'),sum(codes.comm$Strategy=='Reduce'),sum(codes.comm$Strategy=='Suppress'))/length(codes.comm$Decision)*100,
  "Stage"=c("Communication","Communication","Communication")
))

Note that participants used an acknowledgement strategy far more often when defining questions and objectives than they did overall. Multiple participants expressed that they felt this was the most important stage of the research process, so it makes sense that they would spend a lot of time surveying different possible directions and preempting potential issues at this stage in their research. We also see relatively more acknowledgement during literature review, quantitative analysis, and communication than in data collection and meta-analysis. This may reflect the the fact that plans from the outset of an analysis do relatively less to constrain literature review, quantitative analysis, and communication of the review than data collection and meta-analysis. Researchers feel that they need to explore their options when specific mechanisms for reduction (e.g., specific search terms, specific variables to code) are not selected at the outset of the research process. This exploration is a double-edged sword since it no doubt contributes to researcher degrees of freedom in the traditional sense, but it can also serve as a justifiable way for the researcher to orient their analysis toward a practical result. (I’ll find a specific example or two to illustrate this idea in the paper.)

## 21 Levels: Caution Completeness ... Statistical power

Since there are 21 different reasons to analyze, let’s group them by common motivational themes in order to reduce the cardinality of reasons and drill down to the patterns of reasoning behind analytical decision-making in research synthesis.
